snippet.title: ROME TRAVEL GUIDE | Colosseum, Trevi Fountain, Trastavere | Travel Vlog / Food Guide
snippet.description:
More videos for you to (hopefully) enjoy here: 
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1GLHys1MXNg
-~-~~-~~~-~~-~-

Ciao! Travel video time. Rob and I went on our first holiday together to Rome - it was perfecto. We were gladiators at the Colosseum, rode on a 2-man tandem kart and explored the Roman Forum, Palatine Hill, Trevi Fountain, Trastavere, Jewish Ghetto and the Tiber River! Oh, and ate PLENTY of pizza, pasta and gelato of course!

Last Video:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M0aeShHuNvg

Daily updates on Instagram:
http://www.instagram.com/shulikesclothes

replies.textDisplay:
Hello! Thanks for watching :)
You're going to absolutely love Rome - it's an incredible city! I'd definitely walk along the river and stop by Travastere for the local eats and cobble streets. I also love walking about Campo de Fiori - especially when the morning markets are on. They're more 'touristy' but there are so many small side streets you can escape to and get lost in :)
replies.textOriginal:

how much I love Rome?? OMG

Greetings from an italian in London!

how much I love Rome?? OMG 
Missing Italy.... 
Greetings from an italian in London!

replies.textDisplay:
Shu Hii Shu!!!
I don't think they have something in common!! London is very busy city and belongs to the future... Rome is still connected to the past and its progression is going slowly (thx God) especially if you think that's a Capital!! there are many other italian cities like Milan and Turin that are already above Rome in terms of progress. That's why I love Rome! And if you like to see more of Italy I suggest you to go to south Italy!!! there you can find many many places when it looks like the time has stopped at 20 or 30 years ago like in Naples or in Matera or in Sicily (this is where I come from)!!!
anyway living in London for us (southern Italians more then others) is a great experience... it opens yor mind and makes you see things that you couldn't even imagine... eather way bad things or good things.

replies.textDisplay: reorosco Hi, I'm Italian and I have some advices for you. The hotels and b&b near Trevi and Transtevere are really good, but if you want to book a cheeper hotel you can also consider the Termini zone... that's near to the main attractions, the bus and the metro stations. I love Rome and I hope you will love it as much as I do 😊

replies.textDisplay: Thank you for watching! I stayed near the Trevi Fountain and found it to be a great location to the Spanish Steps, the hills, city centre and it's within walking distance to the Colosseum too! If you want to stay outside of the centre, Travastere is a local area FULL of amazing restaurants and bars. It's a lot more quaint! I used the Sony RX100 MK IV - amazing camera and really good with low-light. I've since upgraded to Canon G7X MK II though and the quality is even better so would recommend that! :)
